The paper deals with algorithmic problems related to graphs and connectivity, which are typical topics in computer science. The use of parameterized complexity techniques suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The specific problems studied in the paper, Secluded Path and Secluded Steiner Tree, involve finding paths and trees in graphs, which suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The use of cost functions and optimization criteria suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. The study of parameterizations related to Steiner trees suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.GT (Graph Theory) sub-category. Finally, the use of kernelization techniques suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category.
